IMDB dataset

Cathy-Yuanmeng-Gu

0.1 Background

IMDb (Internet Movie Database) is an Amazon-owned online database of movie-related information. It contains data related to movies, television programmes, video games, and reviews.

0.2 Load the data

In the following, we will look at a subset sample of movies, taken from the Kaggle IMDB 5000 movie dataset

movies <- read_csv(here::here("data", "movies.csv"))

glimpse(movies)

0.3 Inspect the data

First of all, we will take a look at the dataframe to determine if it contains duplicates or missing values to prepare for the following analyses.

#Skim function provides a broad overview of the dataset
movies <- read_csv(here::here("data", "movies.csv"))
options(scipen = 999)
skim(movies) %>%

#duplicated function provides an overview of duplicated values
sum(duplicated(movies))
## [1] 0

As seen above there are no missing values in the dataset. As the sum(duplicated(movies)) function shows, the dataset does not include duplicated entries either.

However, the skim overview shows that the data encompasses 2,961 rows and just 2,907 unique movie titles.

#function shows number of duplicated movie tiles
sum(duplicated(movies$title))
## [1] 54

The sum(duplicated(movies$title)) data clearly shows that there are 54 duplicated movie titles. This number is exactly the difference between the total number of records (2,961) and the number of unique movie titles (2,907).

The following table gives an overview of all duplicated movie titles.

As seen on the table above there are 54 duplicates. For the following analyses we will create a new dataset containing only unique / distinct movie titles.

# Dataframe with only distinct movies
distinct_movies <- movies %>% 
  
  # only keep unique movies
  distinct(title, genre, director, year, .keep_all = TRUE)

The following table displays the number of entries in our previously defined dataset.

distinct_movies %>% 
  #count distinct movies
  summarise(`number of distinct movies:` = n()) %>% 
  #table
  kable(caption = "Distinct Movies") %>%
  #chose styling
  kable_material_dark()
Distinct Movies
number of distinct movies:
2907

Our new dataframe now includes 2,907 distinct movies, thus matching the number of unique titles from the skimr::skim(movies) overview.

0.4 Analyze the data

Now we can start our analyses by taking a look at the count of movies by genre, ranked in descending order.

distinct_movies %>% 
  #group movies by genre
  group_by(genre) %>% 
  #count number of movies per genre
  summarise(`number of movies` = n()) %>% 
  #arrange genres in descending order of number of movies
  arrange(desc(`number of movies`)) %>%
  #table
  kable(caption = "Movies by genre") %>%
  #chose styling
   kable_material_dark() %>% 
  #make table scrollable
  kableExtra::scroll_box(height = "500px")

Next, we will take a closer look at our data by producing a table containing the average gross earnings and budget by genre. For that purpose, we Calculate a variable return_on_budget which shows how many $ did a movie make at the box office for each $ of its budget and rank the genres by this variable in descending order.

distinct_movies %>% 
  #group movies by genre
  group_by(genre) %>% 
  #calculate average values in millions and define single data points per genre
  summarize(avg_gross = mean(gross)/1000000, 
            avg_budget= mean(budget)/1000000) %>% 
  #add and calculate return_on_budget
  mutate(return_on_budget = 100* (avg_gross - avg_budget) / avg_budget) %>% 
  #arrange by return on budget in descending order
  arrange(desc(return_on_budget)) %>% 
  #add titles to the table and columns
  kable(position="center", caption="Average USD gross earnings, budget and return on budget per genre", col.names=c("Genre", "Average gross earnings(m)", "Average budget(m)", "Return on budget(%)")) %>%
  #chose styling
  kable_material_dark() %>%
  #make table scrollable
  kableExtra::scroll_box(height = "500px")

To make further sense of our data, we will produce a table that shows the top 15 directors who have created the highest gross revenue in the box office and include the total gross amount, mean, median, and standard deviation per director.

distinct_movies %>% 
  #group movies by director
  group_by(director) %>% 
  #calculate total gross revenues, mean, median, and standard deviation and summarize them per director
  summarize(sum_gross=sum(gross)/1000000,   
            mean = mean(gross)/1000000,               
            median = median(gross)/1000000,
            sd = sd(gross)/1000000 ) %>% 
  #arrange movies by total gross revenues in descending order
  arrange(desc(sum_gross)) %>%   
  #only display the top 15 directors
  head(15) %>% 
  #add titles to the table and columns
  kable(caption="Top 15 directors by box office gross revenues in USD", col.names=c("Director", "Total gross revenues(m)", "Mean(m)", "Median(m)", "SD(m)")) %>%
  #chose styling
  kable_material_dark() %>%
  #make table scrollable
  kableExtra::scroll_box(height = "500px")

0.5 Visualize the data

Finally, we look at movie ratings and produce a table that describes how ratings are distributed by genre. We use a histogram to visualize how ratings are distributed.

distinct_movies %>% 
  #group movies by genre
  group_by(genre) %>% 
  #summarize mean, min, max, sd of ratings per genre
  summarize(mean= mean(rating), 
            min=min(rating),
            max=max(rating),
            sd=sd(rating)) %>% 
  #arrange in descending order
  arrange(desc(mean)) %>% 
  #add titles to the table and columns
  kable(caption="Distribution of ratings by genre", col.names = c("Genre", "Mean", "Min", "Max", "SD")) %>%
  #chose styling
  kable_material_dark() %>%
    #make table scrollable
   kableExtra::scroll_box(height = "500px")

In order to make further sense of our data we will now examine the relationship between gross revenues and facebook likes the cast of each movie receives by way of a scatterplot. This analysis will allow us to determine if the number of facebook likes a cast has received is an indicator of the money a movie will make at the box office.

The analysis shows that there is no correlation at all between the number of facebook likes a cast receives and the gross box office revenues a movie makes.

However, there maybe other variables that may indicate a movies financial success at the box office. The next variable we will analyze is a movies budget, i.e.the budgets relationship to a movies box office revenues.

The plot clearly displays a positive correlation between a movies budget and the gross box office revenues it makes, thus qualifying a movies budget as a good indicator of its financial success. This relationship is particularly intuitive since movies with a higher budget i.e.higher expenses must generate higher revenues on order to be profitable. Beyond that, if a movie has a high budget the spending on marketing as well as the overall quality of production may be higher, thus attracting more viewers.

To end our analyses we will determine how the relationship between a movies box office revenues and its rating varies by genre.

The plot displays a surprising pattern. Especially for movies in the action and adventure genres there seems to be a positive correlation between a movies rating and the box office revenues it generates. However, for other genres the data displays a straight line indicating no correlation at all. Especially interesting is that the pattern seems to flatten for more special genres. I would assume, that some genres like horror, fantasy, mystery or science fiction attract an audience who are especially interested in that type of movies and who are likely to watch a movie in their preferred genre regardless of its rating. Movies in the categories adventure, action, and drama, however, seem to address a broader group of viewers. Hence, in these genres viewers may be more likely to base their decision whether to watch a movie or not on ratings. Lastly, for some categories like thriller, western, musical, or romance the available data is insufficient to make an inference.
